	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Shaman Guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:"></a> | 
		            6/14/1999 2:43:15 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Shaman Guide<BR>
<BR>
To be a shaman is to have a special relationship with the spirits of our world. This guide is designed to help you find your way along the true path.<BR>
<BR>
It seems that the vile trolls and thoughtless ogres have patterned their shamanantic trials after we barbarians so their progress will roughly mirror our younger shamans.<BR>
<BR>
Initiation:<BR>
Turn in your letter to the guild leader. Speak to her and all the other learned shamans about their experiences and maybe, if you make a good impression, you will be given a quest like collecting goblin necklaces or bone chips. Also practice only once on your Sense heading and using one-handed blunt weapons. You will eventually want to learn other weapons like 2handed blunt though&#8230;<BR>
Cross the water toward the Everfrost peaks. I recommend swimming instead of taking the boat across. Not only will this wash the scent of the campfires from your furs but will begin to teach you how to swim.<BR>
Before you leave the merchant tents make sure you have memorized you spells Inner Fire and minor Healing. Also make sure Inner Fire is always going. If you are ever at full mana and not about to go into a major battle recast Inner Fire. The benefits of doing this are many fold as you will later see.<BR>
The First Hunt:<BR>
I will leave this to the lessons you have learned from other teachers sufficing it to say kill all the skeletons, goblins and gnoll pups you can. They are the best cash cows and the greatest threats to our people. When an enemy is carrying a weapon get them first, especially skeletons carrying staffs. Hunt alone until you reach at least the 4th circle of power.<BR>
Hunting alone is not to say ignore your brother and sister barbarians around you. It is your responsibility to keep each and every one of them alive. They will remember you for your aid.<BR>
Buffing:<BR>
As a shaman your value will increase to our people incredibly when you hunt with friends after the 4th circle of power. 5th is when you will get your first enhancement spells. To avoid confusion in the future, clerics receive spells that heal, protect by absorbing damage and make one harder to hit. We enhance how well a companion attacks, damage they inflict, moves, heals, with some protection spells too.<BR>
While it is important to keep everyone alive during a fight, healing and buffing someone outside of your group after a fight is a precarious situation. Your first priority is keeping everyone around you alive, Second is to have your party operating at maximum efficiency (fully healed and buffed), Third making sure non combatants are buffed and healed (so long as this doesn't conflict with #1 or #2).<BR>
If someone asks you for healing or buffing and they are not in a fight and your own group isn't fully healed and buffed how can you in good conscious ignore your hunting party and use your mana on this stranger?<BR>
A polite, &quot;I'm sorry but I must heal and buff my party first&quot;. Many people have opted to charge few gold or a pp to cast things like Spirit Of The Wolf on strangers. Personally I feel if they are willing to wait I will cast for them.<BR>
Spells: (1st, 5th, and 9th rank) <BR>
Inner Fire, Strength, Dex aura, Cat feet, Spirit Of Wolf, Spirit of the bear(I cast on warrior only usually), Tainted Breath, Frost rift and your best healing spell are going to be heavily used spells through 13th level and many beyond<BR>
Other spells include that are worthwhile are Summon food/water, Spirit pouch (no weight carrying bag great for heavy items), serpent sight, turtle skin and gate are very valuable. Serpent sight is also a crucial spell for our people. The closest place it is sold is in Qeynos. <BR>
Spells: (14th)<BR>
Spirit Strike(finally a good dd spell! 74-75 pts damage), bind affinity, Disempower(not too thrilled with this one so far), and of course root. Also Turtle skin is a great protective spell too.<BR>
Skills:<BR>
Pick up (1 point in) 2 handed blunt asap and switch out between using a cracked staff and shield and the great worn staff so both skills will be maxed out. I used to only use the 2handed staff vs low blue creatures as I was just learning the 2 handed staff.<BR>
Put a point in meditate the second you reach 8th level. This is a crucial skill.<BR>
Spell skills will go up automatically and you will find yourself using all spheres of spells and keeping them high if you continually summon food and buff your charges.<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds:<BR>
The Everfrost plains are a great place to hunt. I would split your time between the orcs and calves on the plains and hunting Black Burrow. BB will help your cash flow immensely. Even the Plains of West Karana are good spots for you. The bandits and gnolls should fear you.<BR>
The cats over on Kerra Island provide another excellent hunting grounds. The big-headed mages will love their first taste of shamantic magic, especially when the Kerran High Guard is chasing them down.<BR>
Travel everywhere!<BR>
Split Paw is a great spot once you reach higher levels. 10-16ish.<BR>
<BR>
Tactics:<BR>
A shaman is a great person to lure monsters back to a hunting party. Cast Tainted breath on your target and trot back to your hunting party. The creature will take damage as it follows you back to party. Be sure not to get too far ahead or you will lose it.<BR>
Spirit Strike takes a long time to cast so if I will be in melee I will open with Spirit Strike since it will be my only real good chance to get it off, followed by tainted breath and disempower. Once in melee I will use about half my mana on offense (on a tough fight of course), and the last half healing my companions.<BR>
<BR>
Grouping:<BR>
I would suggest that you begin grouping all the time beginning at 5th level. Start with just enough people to kill whatever you are hunting. Hunting elites with 6 15th level adventurers is overkill and you will learn next to nothing on your hunt. If you decide not to group until higher levels you will find yourself over-whelmed by the pace of the battle and many will die by your inappropriate actions or inaction.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Enjoy the hunt!<BR>
<BR>
Brotherwolf<BR>
Shaman - Innoruuk<BR>
Keepers of Norrath<BR>
<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
